	<article> 
		<h1>LearningStudio Hello World</h1>
		
		<p>The best way to learn about the LearningStudio Course APIs is to play with them. This Hello World application takes care the background work like authentication or making HTTP requests, and lets you jump directly to the APIs. Ultimately, you'll still need to read up on the documentation and do the programming work, and for that we have lots of <a href="http://pdn.pearson.com/learningstudio">great documentation</a> and some helpful <a href="http://pdn.pearson.com/learningstudio/code/libraries">code libraries</a> to streamline your development.</p>
		
		<p>For now, the Hello World acts as a proxy to the APIs. You can use it in your browser or in an API console like Postman or Fiddler. If you haven't already, you'll need to configure Hello World with your API credentials. You can get an API key, sandbox courses, and a sandbox user <a href="http://pdn.pearson.com/learningstudio/get-a-key">through the PDN portal</a>.</p> 
		
		<h2>Configuring Hello World</h2> 
		
		<p>The <code>HelloWorldConfig.ini</code> file is in the <code>Resources</code> directory. Open it, and add your unique credentials:</p> 
		<table> 
			<tr>
				<th>Property Name</th>
				<th>Value</th>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td><code>applicationId</code></td>
				<td>Use the unique Application ID that is provided when you <a href="http://pdn.pearson.com/learningstudio/get-a-key">register a new application on the PDN</a>.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td><code>applicationName</code></td>
				<td>This can be any string that identifies your application. Avoid Spaces, e.g., <code>MyAppName</code>.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td><code>clientString</code></td>
				<td>LearningStudio instances are identified by a <a href="http://pdn.pearson.com/learningstudio/sis/overview/data-structure">client string</a>. For the Sandbox Campus, this value is <code>gbtestc</code>. If you are a LearningStudio client and want to test on your own campus, speak with your Strategic Customer Operations team to get your client string.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td><code>consumerKey</code></td>
				<td>Use the Token Key Moniker that is provided when you <a href="http://pdn.pearson.com/learningstudio/get-a-key">register a new application on the PDN</a>. If you are a LearningStudio client and want to test on your own campus, speak with your Strategic Customer Operations team to get your campus API keys.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td><code>consumerSecret</code></td>
				<td>Use the Shared Secret that is provided when you <a href="http://pdn.pearson.com/learningstudio/get-a-key">register a new application on the PDN</a>. If you are a LearningStudio client and want to test on your own campus, speak with your Strategic Customer Operations team to get your campus API keys.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td><code>userName</code></td>
				<td>Use one of the usernames that is provided when you <a href="http://pdn.pearson.com/learningstudio/get-a-key">register a new application on the PDN</a>. We suggest using a teacher's account with Hello World, but you can also use a student's to compare the different levels of access to APIs.</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
			
		<h2>Making Basic Requests</h2> 
		
		<p>Basic <code>GET</code> requests can be made in your browser, and it's easy to toggle between different authentication methods.</p> 
		<p>It appears you have installed Hello World at this address</p><pre><code><script type="text/javascript">
		var URL = document.URL; 
		URL.replace('index.php',''); 
		document.write(URL); 
		</script></code></pre>
		<p>To make an API call, you will simply add on to this URL with the OAuth type, and the API endpoint.</p>
		<p>First, you can use either OAuth 1 or OAuth 2. When using OAuth 2, you are acting as the user, so you have a few additional capabilities like writing thread posts or getting one's own grades. Choose the OAuth method by adding either <code>oauth1</code> or <code>oauth2</code> to the URL. For example: </p><pre><code><script type="text/javascript">
		var URL = document.URL; 
		URL.replace('/index.php','');
		if(URL.substr(URL.length - 1)!='/') URL+='/';
		document.write(URL); 
		</script>oauth1</code><br><code><script type="text/javascript">
		var URL = document.URL; 
		URL.replace('/index.php','');
		if(URL.substr(URL.length - 1)!='/') URL+='/';
		document.write(URL); 
		</script>oauth2</code></pre>
		<p>Next, add on the full path of the API you want to call. For example, if you wanted to get a list of courses for a user, using OAuth 1, that API endpoint is <code>/users/{userId}/courses</code>, and would look like this: </p>
		<pre><code><script type="text/javascript">
		var URL = document.URL; 
		URL.replace('/index.php','');
		if(URL.substr(URL.length - 1)!='/') URL+='/';
		document.write(URL); 
		</script>oauth1/users/000000/courses</code></pre>
		<p>Any <code>GET</code> request can be tried in the browser. Here's a few more examples:</p> 
		<pre><code><script type="text/javascript">
		var URL = document.URL; 
		URL.replace('/index.php','');
		if(URL.substr(URL.length - 1)!='/') URL+='/';
		document.write(URL); 
		</script>oauth2/me</code><br><code><script type="text/javascript">
		var URL = document.URL; 
		URL.replace('/index.php','');
		if(URL.substr(URL.length - 1)!='/') URL+='/';
		document.write(URL); 
		</script>oauth2/me/courses</code><br><code><script type="text/javascript">
		var URL = document.URL; 
		URL.replace('/index.php','');
		if(URL.substr(URL.length - 1)!='/') URL+='/';
		document.write(URL); 
		</script>oauth2/courses/0000000/itemHierarchy</code></pre>
		
		<h2>Use an API Console for <code>POST</code> and <code>PUT</code> Requests</h2>
		
		<p>To really start playing with the APIs you should experiment with creating and updating data using <code>POST</code> and <code>PUT</code> requests. This is best done with an API console like Postman or Fiddler. Simply use the same URLs as above in the console, and change the settings to send along the appropriate request. Be sure to review the API documentation to properly format your request. </p> 
		<p>Here's an example of Postman being configured to <code>POST</code> a new response to a threaded discussion:</p> 
		
		<img src="data:image/png;base64," width="800">
		
		<p>That's all there is to it - once you've added your credentials to the configuration file, you can start making API calls at will. We suggest signing into your LearningStudio sandbox courses to see how and where the APIs work alongside the user interface.</p>
		<p>When you're ready to start coding your own application, check out the <a href="http://pdn.pearson.com/learningstudio/code/libraries">LearningStudio Code Libraries</a> to make development easier - those libraries streamline the heavy lifting such as authentication and HTTP requests.</p> 
		
	</article> 	
